        "## Model Performance\n",
        "\n",
        "The Random Forest model achieved an R² of 0.526 and Adjusted R² of 0.517, explaining approximately 52% of salary variation. Compared to the Multiple Linear Regression model (R² = 0.378), Random Forest improved explanatory power by nearly 15 percentage points. The lower RMSE ($30,791) and MAE ($22,192) also confirm better prediction accuracy. The minimal gap between R² and Adjusted R² indicates that the features included in the model contribute meaningfully rather than inflating performance artificially.\n",
        "\n",
        "## Feature Importance\n",
        "\n",
        "Unlike MLR which outputs coefficients, Random Forest provides feature importance scores that indicate how much each variable contributes to salary prediction.\n",
        "\n",
        "The most influential variable is **employment type (Full-time > 32 hours)**, with an importance score of 0.360 — far exceeding all other features. This suggests that whether a job is full-time or part-time has the strongest impact on salary, more so than job title or skills.\n",
        "\n",
        "Among job titles, **Data Engineer Analytics** stands out as the highest-paying role (importance: 0.059), consistent with strong market demand for data engineering skills. Among skills, **communication** (0.085) and **planning** (0.076) rank highest, suggesting that soft skills play a meaningful role in salary differentiation alongside technical abilities.\n",
        "\n",
        "Geographic location (state-level) shows relatively low importance across all states, indicating that location alone is not a strong salary predictor once job title, skills, and employment type are controlled for.\n",
        "\n",
        "## Model Limitations\n",
        "\n",
        "Despite the improvement over MLR, the model still leaves approximately 48% of salary variance unexplained. Key factors not available in the dataset — such as years of experience, education level, company size, and individual negotiation — likely account for the remaining variance. Future work could incorporate these variables to further improve predictive accuracy."
